## 2. For Loops

### 2.1 Loop Through Files — Wildcard `*`

`*` is a **wildcard** — shell automatically expands it to all matching files!

```bash
# All files in current directory
for file in *; do
    echo $file
done

# Only txt files
for file in *.txt; do
    echo $file
done

# Only log files
for file in *.log; do
    echo $file
done

# Files starting with "file"
for file in file*; do
    echo $file
done
```

---

### 2.2 Loop Through Numbers

```bash
# Way 1 — list numbers manually
for i in 1 2 3 4 5; do
    echo $i
done

# Way 2 — range (clean and simple!)
for i in {1..10}; do
    echo $i
done

# Way 3 — like C language (more control)
for ((i=1; i<=10; i++)); do
    echo $i
done

# Step by 2
for i in {1..10..2}; do    # 1 3 5 7 9
    echo $i
done

# Count down
for i in {10..1}; do
    echo $i
done
```

---

### 2.3 Loop Through Custom List

```bash
# Inline list
for color in red green blue yellow; do
    echo $color
done

# List stored in variable
fruits="apple banana mango"
for fruit in $fruits; do
    echo $fruit
done

# List of servers
servers="server1 server2 server3"
for server in $servers; do
    echo "Connecting to $server"
done
```

---

### 2.4 Loop Through Command Output

Any command that returns multiple lines can be used with `$()` !

```bash
# find command — loop through all txt files
for file in $(find . -name "*.txt"); do
    echo $file
done

# ls command
for file in $(ls *.log); do
    echo $file
done

# Read from a file
for line in $(cat filelist.txt); do
    echo $line
done

# Loop through all running processes
for pid in $(pgrep bash); do
    echo "Bash process: $pid"
done
```

Simple rule:
> **Anything that returns multiple lines can go inside `$()` and for loop will traverse each item!**

---

### 2.5 Loop Control — break and continue

```bash
# continue — skip current iteration
for file in *; do
    if [ -d "$file" ]; then
        continue    # skip directories, go to next file
    fi
    echo $file
done

# break — stop the loop entirely
for i in {1..10}; do
    if [ $i -eq 5 ]; then
        break      # stop at 5
    fi
    echo $i
done
```

| Command | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `continue` | skip this iteration, go to next |
| `break` | stop the loop entirely |

