## 3. Bulk File Organizer — Key Concepts

```bash
#!/bin/bash
cd ./testfiles

mkdir -p /workspaces/logs    # create log dir if not exists

for file in *; do
    # skip directories and script itself
    if [ -d "$file" ] || [ "$file" == "$0" ]; then
        continue
    fi

    extension="${file##*.}"    # extract extension

    if [ $extension == "txt" ]; then
        mkdir -p text
        mv $file text
        echo "$(date) - Moved $file to /text" >> /workspaces/logs/challenge3log

    elif [ $extension == "jpg" ] || [ $extension == "png" ]; then
        mkdir -p images
        mv $file images
        echo "$(date) - Moved $file to /images" >> /workspaces/logs/challenge3log

    elif [ $extension == "sh" ]; then
        mkdir -p scripts
        mv $file scripts
        echo "$(date) - Moved $file to /scripts" >> /workspaces/logs/challenge3log

    else
        echo "$(date) - Skipped $file (unknown extension)" >> /workspaces/logs/challenge3log
    fi
done
```

Key concepts used:
- `${file##*.}` — extract file extension
- `mkdir -p` — create folder only if not exists
- `mv` — move file to folder
- `-d "$file"` — check if item is a directory
- `$0` — script's own name
- `continue` — skip current iteration
- `||` — OR condition
- `>>` — append to log file
- `$(date)` — current timestamp

